SIMPLE: ruffle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ruffle
<hw>Ruf"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Ruffled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ruffling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Ruff</er>
a plaited collar, a drum beat, a tumult: cf. OD. <ets>ruyffelen</ets> to
wrinkle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make into a ruff; to draw or
contract into puckers, plaits, or folds; to wrinkle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with ruffles; <as>as, to <ex>ruffle</ex>
a shirt</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To oughen or disturb the surface of; to make uneven
by agitation or commotion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fantastic revelries . . . that so often <qex>ruffled</qex> the
placid bosom of the Nile.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She smoothed the <qex>ruffled</qex> seas.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To erect in a ruff, as feathers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[the swan] <qex>ruffles</qex> her pure cold plume.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To beat with the ruff or ruffle,
as a drum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To discompose; to agitate; to disturb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These <qex>ruffle</qex> the tranquillity of the mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But, ever after, the small violence done⟦br⟧
Rankled in him and <qex>ruffled</qex> all his heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To throw into disorder or confusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where best⟦br⟧
He might the <qex>ruffled</qex> foe infest.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To throw together in a disorderly manner.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>ruffled</qex> up falen leaves in heap.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To ruffle the feathers of</b></col>, <cd>to exite the
resentment of; to irritate.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruffle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ruffle
<hw>Ruf"fle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Perhaps of
different origin from <ets>ruffle</ets> to wrinkle; cf. OD.
<ets>roffeln</ets>, <ets>roffen</ets>, to pander, LG.
<ets>raffein</ets>, Dan. <ets>ruffer</ets> a pimp. Cf.
<er>Rufflan</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To grow rough, boisterous, or
turbulent.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The night comes on, and the bleak winds⟦br⟧
Do sorely <qex>ruffle</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become disordered; to play loosely; to
flutter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On his right shoulder his thick mane reclined,⟦br⟧
<qex>Ruffles</qex> at speed, and dances in the wind.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be rough; to jar; to be in contention; hence, to
put on airs; to swagger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They would <qex>ruffle</qex> with jurors.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gallants who <qex>ruffled</qex> in silk and embroidery.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruffle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ruffle
<hw>Ruf"fle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Ruffle</er>, <pos>v. t. &
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is ruffled; specifically, a
strip of lace, cambric, or other fine cloth, plaited or gathered on one
edge or in the middle, and used as a trimming; a frill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A state of being ruffled or disturbed; disturbance;
agitation; commotion; <as>as, to put the mind in a
<ex>ruffle</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A low, vibrating beat of a drum,
not so loud as a roll; -- called also <altname>ruff</altname>.</def>
<rj><au>H. L. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The connected series of large egg
capsules, or oothecae, of any one of several species of American marine
gastropods of the genus <gen>Fulgur</gen>. See
<er>Ootheca</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ruffle of a boot</b></col>, <cd>the top turned down, and
scalloped or plaited.</cd> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruffleless</ent>⟦br⟧
